{"ts":"2026-06-27T13:15:19.599Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_end","contentType":"reasoning","reasoning":"**Prioritizing API Development**\n\nI'm feeling excited! The initial concept seems promising. Now, I'm shifting focus to practical execution. My immediate plan involves building out the dashboard summary APIs first. I am leaning towards creating a draft API skeleton, but I am first thinking through how to structure the file system. My intended route is GET /api/v1/dashboard/client, in the file `app/api/v1/dashboard/client/`.\n\n\n**Refining Internal Design Plan**\n\nI'm now diving deeper into planning, specifically for the dashboard summary APIs. It turns out that I need to clarify the structure of the data that the API should be returning. I'm focusing on defining the API's internal design plan, covering the section narrative, intended user, and its layout strategy, to ensure structured enterprise-grade summary metrics. I'm taking a rigorous approach, as I'm thinking carefully about the best ways to structure the API's returned data.\n\n\n**Defining API Endpoints**\n\nI'm now zeroing in on defining the specific API endpoints, and I am excited by how they are taking shape. I'm focusing on creating clear, structured data outputs, structured as JSON payloads. This structure will work as an audit ledger with continuous telemetry validation. My plan involves two key endpoints: one for clients, one for admins. The `/api/v1/dashboard/client` endpoint will provide a client-specific view of invoices and support tunnels, while the admin view will aggregate data across all clients.\n\n\n**Implementing API Error Handling**\n\nI'm now prioritizing comprehensive error handling. I'm focusing on crafting consistent, user-friendly responses for issues like unauthorized access or internal errors. My plan is to ensure that mobile clients and secure enclaves receive highly structured, quick-parsing JSON payloads with sensible record limits. I'll modify `lib/api-auth.ts`, and create `app/api/v1/dashboard/client/route.ts` and `app/api/v1/dashboard/admin/route.ts` while leaving landing page files and AI tools untouched. I will also incorporate similar logic used for authentication in `/app/api/v1/projects/route.ts`.\n\n\n**Refactoring Authentication Logic**\n\nI'm now refining the authentication logic. I'm considering the best place to define and utilize the `getAuthCaller` function. I'm weighing whether to create a helper or keep it local to the client and admin route files to maintain self-containment. It seems cleanest to copy the logic into those two route files. This approach mirrors the established patterns in other sections of the codebase like projects, ai-operations, and governance.\n\n\n**Clarifying Dashboard Data Retrieval**\n\nI'm now clarifying the specifics for the client dashboard data retrieval, and ensuring the data definitions align with the API requirements. I'm taking the time to define the status values: for \"active projects,\" only projects with `\"active\"` status. I am doing the same for the other resources in the dashboard, like AI operations. For example, \"open support tickets\" considers those where `status !== \"RESOLVED\" && status !== \"resolved\"`. I am making sure to validate data to match these clear definitions.\n\n\n**Defining Governance Logic**\n\nI'm now getting into the detailed logic for governance items. Specifically, I'm focusing on defining what qualifies as \"active.\" I've decided to count governance items as active if their `status` is not `\"remediated\"`, `\"Remediated\"`, `\"archived\"`, or `\"completed\"`. I'm going to take this approach for all resources. Now, I'll specify exact counts and records to return in the client dashboard API.\n\n\n\n**Calculating Dashboard Summaries**\n\nI'm now zeroing in on the specific calculations for the client dashboard summaries. I'm focusing on defining counts for active projects, operations, documents, invoices, open support tickets, and governance items. I am also calculating recent records by last update dates for various resources such as projects, operations, documents, invoices, and support tickets. I'm excited by this implementation step.\n\n\n**Structuring JSON Outputs**\n\nI'm now focusing on ensuring a clean and consistent JSON response structure for the dashboard API. I'm prioritizing readability and ease of parsing for the client. The structure includes counts for active/total resources, and \"recent\" arrays for each category: projects, AI operations, documents, invoices, support tickets, and governance. The \"recent\" arrays will be sorted by dates and truncated to the top 5.\n\n\n**Defining API Authentication**\n\nI'm now focusing on authenticating client dashboard API requests. I've defined allowed roles: `gff_admin`, `client_admin`, and `client_member`. For `/api/v1/dashboard/client`, I'll allow any authenticated user, returning their associated client's dashboard. For `gff_admin` users, I'll support a `client_id` query parameter to view other clients' data, or default to their own. Other roles will be limited to their own.\n\n\n**Implementing Client Dashboard API**\n\nI'm now in the thick of implementing the client dashboard API, starting with `app/api/v1/dashboard/client/route.ts`. The first thing I'm doing is verifying the file structure, importing necessary modules and double-checking imports. I'm focusing on defining imports and typings, to avoid any TypeScript errors, by working through each level of the directory structure. My main goal is to restrict the client API logic to their associated `client_id` for enclave security.\n\n\n"}}
{"ts":"2026-06-27T13:15:19.602Z","type":"agent_event","event":{"type":"content_start","contentType":"tool","toolName":"editor","toolCallId":"0p2gcb3q","input":{"path":"/Users/ayushbansal/Documents/GitHub/hirezapp_landing_page/app/api/v1/dashboard/client/route.ts","new_text":"import { NextResponse } from \"next/server\";\nimport { \n  API_MOCK_USERS, \n  API_MOCK_PROJECTS, \n  API_MOCK_AI_OPERATIONS,\n  API_MOCK_INVOICES,\n  API_MOCK_GOVERNANCE,\n  API_MOCK_DOCUMENTS,\n  API_MOCK_SUPPORT_TICKETS,\n  verifyJwt, \n  MockUserDbEntry, \n  getClientIdFromAssociation \n} from \"@/lib/api-auth\";\n\nexport const runtime = \"nodejs\";\n\nfunction getAuthCaller(req: Request) {\n  const auth = req.headers.get(\"authorization\");\n  if (!auth?.startsWith(\"Bearer \")) {\n    return { status: 401, error: \"Unauthorized\", msg: \"Missing/malformed Authorization header.\" };\n  }\n  const decoded = verifyJwt(auth.substring(7));\n  if (!decoded?.email) {\n    return { status: 401, error: \"Unauthorized\", msg: \"Invalid/expired access token.\" };\n  }\n  const user = (API_MOCK_USERS as Record<string, MockUserDbEntry>)[decoded.email.toLowerCase().trim()];\n  if (!user) {\n    return { status: 401, error: \"Unauthorized\", msg: \"Authorized user not found.\" };\n  }\n  if (user.status === \"inactive\") {\n    return { status: 403, error: \"Forbidden\", msg: \"This account is inactive.\" };\n  }\n  return { caller: user };\n}\n\nexport async function GET(req: Request) {\n  try {\n    const auth = getAuthCaller(req);\n    if (\"status\" in auth) {\n      return NextResponse.json({ success: false, error: auth.error, message: auth.msg }, { status: auth.status });\n    }\n    const { caller } = auth;\n\n    // Resolve client ID for filtering\n    let callerClientId = getClientIdFromAssociation(caller.clientAssociation);\n\n    const { searchParams } = new URL(req.url);\n    const requestedClientId = searchParams.get(\"client_id\");\n\n    if (caller.role === \"gff_admin\") {\n      // Admins can inspect any client's portal dashboard\n      if (requestedClientId) {\n        callerClientId = requestedClientId;\n      } else {\n        // Default to a valid client ID if none is requested\n        callerClientId = \"client-001\";\n      }\n    } else {\n      // Enforce security boundary for non-admin callers\n      if (requestedClientId && requestedClientId !== callerClientId) {\n        return NextResponse.json(\n          { success: false, error: \"Forbidden\", message: \"Access denied to requested client's dashboard.\" },\n          { status: 403 }\n        );\n      }\n    }\n\n    // Retrieve database records filtered by the caller's client_id\n    const clientProjects = Object.values(API_MOCK_PROJECTS).filter(p => p.client_id === callerClientId);\n    const clientOps = Object.values(API_MOCK_AI_OPERATIONS).filter(o => o.client_id === callerClientId);\n    const clientDocs = Object.values(API_MOCK_DOCUMENTS).filter(d => d.client_id === callerClientId);\n    const clientInvoices = Object.values(API_MOCK_INVOICES).filter(i => i.client_id === callerClientId);\n    const clientTickets = Object.values(API_MOCK_SUPPORT_TICKETS).filter(t => t.client_id === callerClientId);\n    const clientGov = Object.values(API_MOCK_GOVERNANCE).filter(g => g.client_id === callerClientId);\n\n    // Calculate aggregated counts\n    const totalProjects = clientProjects.length;\n    const activeProjectsCount = clientProjects.filter(p => p.status === \"active\").length;\n\n    const totalOps = clientOps.length;\n    const activeOperationsCount = clientOps.filter(o => o.status === \"active\").length;\n\n    const totalDocs = clientDocs.length;\n    const verifiedDocsCount = clientDocs.filter(d => d.status === \"Verified\").length;\n\n    const totalInvoices = clientInvoices.length;\n    const unpaidInvoicesCount = clientInvoices.filter(i => i.status === \"unpaid\" || i.status === \"processing\").length;\n\n    const totalTickets = clientTickets.length;\n    const openSupportTicketsCount = clientTickets.filter(t => t.status !== \"RESOLVED\" && t.status !== \"resolved\").length;\n\n    const totalGov = clientGov.length;\n    const flaggedGovCount = clientGov.filter(g => g.status === \"Flagged\" || g.status === \"Critical\" || g.severity === \"Critical\").length;\n\n    // Retrieve sorted recent records (top 5 max for performance)\n    const recentProjects = [...clientProjects]\n      .sort((a, b) => new Date(b.lastUpdated || \"\").getTime() - new Date(a.lastUpdated || \"\").getTime())\n      .slice(0, 5);\n\n    const recentOperations = [...clientOps]\n      .sort((a, b) => new Date(b.lastUpdated || \"\").getTime() - new Date(a.lastUpdated || \"\").getTime())\n      .slice(0, 5);\n\n    const recentDocuments = [...clientDocs]\n      .sort((a, b) => new Date(b.lastUpdated || \"\").getTime() - new Date(a.lastUpdated || \"\").getTime())\n      .slice(0, 5);\n\n    const recentInvoices = [...clientInvoices]\n      .sort((a, b) => new Date(b.lastUpdated || \"\").getTime() - new Date(a.lastUpdated || \"\").getTime())\n      .slice(0, 5);\n\n    const recentSupportTickets = [...clientTickets]\n      .sort((a, b) => new Date(b.createdDate || \"\").getTime() - new Date(a.createdDate || \"\").getTime())\n      .slice(0, 5);\n\n    const recentGovernanceItems = [...clientGov]\n      .sort((a, b) => new Date(b.lastUpdated || \"\").getTime() - new Date(a.lastUpdated || \"\").getTime())\n      .slice(0, 5);\n\n    // Build the high-fidelity structured summary response\n    return NextResponse.json({\n      success: true,\n      client_id: callerClientId,\n      summary: {\n        projects: {\n          activeCount: activeProjectsCount,\n          totalCount: totalProjects,\n          recent: recentProjects\n        },\n        aiOperations: {\n          activeCount: activeOperationsCount,\n          totalCount: totalOps,\n          recent: recentOperations\n        },\n        documents: {\n          verifiedCount: verifiedDocsCount,\n          totalCount: totalDocs,\n          recent: recentDocuments\n        },\n        invoices: {\n          unpaidCount: unpaidInvoicesCount,\n          totalCount: totalInvoices,\n          recent: recentInvoices\n        },\n        supportTickets: {\n          openCount: openSupportTicketsCount,\n          totalCount: totalTickets,\n          recent: recentSupportTickets\n        },\n        governance: {\n          flaggedCount: flaggedGovCount,\n          totalCount: totalGov,\n          recent: recentGovernanceItems\n        }\n      }\n    });\n\n  } catch (err) {\n    console.error(\"Error generating client dashboard summary:\", err);\n    return NextResponse.json({ success: false, error: \"Internal Server Error\" }, { status: 500 });\n  }\n}\n"}}}
